**who —** VIRUSES — a life-science sphere — the brainless mind

**what —** Not quite alive and not quite not — a virus is a scrap of genetic code in a protein shell that does nothing on its own, until it meets a cell. Then it hijacks the machinery of life to copy itself, evolves, adapts, and outnumbers every living thing on Earth. The clearest case of 'life-like' without being, settledly, alive.

**where —** intelligence without a brain  Framework inputs: the living; the rule; the signal; the open question  Conductor / external anchor: ROOT0 (catalogued into UD0)

**why —** Not quite alive and not quite not — a virus is a scrap of genetic code in a protein shell that does nothing on its own, until it meets a cell. Then it hijacks the machinery of life to copy itself, evolves, adapts, and outnumbers every living thing on Earth. The clearest case of 'life-like' without being, settledly, alive.

**how —** Crystallized from the public record of the science.

**◌ the mythos —** Not quite alive and not quite not — a virus is a scrap of genetic code in a protein shell that does nothing on its own, until it meets a cell. Then it hijacks the machinery of life to copy itself, evolves, adapts, and outnumbers every living thing on Earth. The clearest case of 'life-like' without being, settledly, alive. where a mind appears with no neurons in it

